{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b18dfdc4-600f-42b5-acd2-fb9e61d62b04","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your updated SDK. This is what you need when workloads are out of date.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *current* versions of workloads to fix corrupted installations. It doesn't fetch newer versions.\n\nSince the problem is a version mismatch after an SDK update, `update` is the right fix:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf builds still fail afterward, also verify your MAUI workload is installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"52a05924-f6e8-4f85-95af-71c4fb87d766","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` to fix their .NET MAUI build issue after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require any tool calls - I can answer it directly.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` - Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions. This is what you want when workloads are out of date relative to a new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` - Reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations. It doesn't update versions, just repairs the current ones.\n\n\n- Since the issue stems from workloads being out of sync with the new SDK, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run.","outputTokens":356,"requestId":"E849:21DC3D:2573A38:2979D6E:69F93E61"},"id":"a1fb70e0-cb50-455e-aa98-4b9001724840","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:48:41.578Z","parentId":"b5fa6590-5b59-473b-865d-92337849306d"}
